cabinet.*April 1947  Greenwood becomes without Portfolio. Lord Inman succeeds Greenwood as Privy Seal. William Francis Hare, Lord Listowel succeeds Lord Pethick-Lawrence as of State for India and Burma.*July 1947  The Affairs Office becomes the of Commonwealth Relations. Addison remains at the head.*August 1947  India and Burma Office becomes Burma office with independence. Lord Listowel remains in office.*September 1947  Sir Cripps becomes Minister of Economic Affairs. Wilson succeeds Cripps as of the Board of Trade. Greenwood retires from the Bench.*October 1947  Lord Addison succeeds Lord Inman as Privy Seal, remaining also of the House of Lords. Noel-Baker succeeds Lord Addison as of State for Commonwealth Relations. Woodburn succeeds Westwood as of State for Scotland. The of Fuel and Power, Shinwell, leaves the Cabinet.*November 1947  Sir Cripps succeeds Dalton as of the Exchequer.*January 1948  The Office is abolished with independence.*May 1948: Dalton re-enters the Cabinet as of the Duchy of Lancaster. Lord Pakenham enters the Cabinet as of Civil Aviation.*July 1948: Lord Addison becomes Paymaster-General.*April 1949: Lord Addison ceases to be Paymaster-General, remaining Privy Seal and of the House of Lords. His successor as Paymaster-General is not in the Cabinet.Attlees cabinet 195051In February 1950, a substantial reshuffle took place following the General Election:*Clement Attlee: Prime Minister*Lord Jowitt: Chancellor*Herbert Morrison: Prime Minister, President of the Council and of the House of Commons*Lord Addison: Privy Seal and of the House of Lords*Sir Stafford Cripps: of the Exchequer*Bevin: of State for Foreign Affairs*Chuter Ede: of State for the Home Department*Griffiths: of State for the Colonies*Gordon Walker: of State for Commonwealth Relations*Wilson: of the Board of Trade*Lord Alexander of Hillsborough: of the Duchy of Lancaster*Tomlinson: Minister of Education*McNeil: of State for Scotland*Tom Williams: of Agriculture and Fisheries*Isaacs: Minister of Labour and National Service*Bevan: Minister of Health*Shinwell: Minister of Defence*Dalton: Minister of Town and Country PlanningChanges*October 1950: Gaitskell succeeds Sir Stafford Cripps as Chancellor of the Exchequer.*January 1951: Aneurin Bevan succeeds George Isaacs as Minister of Labour and National Service. Bevans successor as Minister of Health is not in the cabinet. Hugh Daltons post is renamed Minister of Local Government and Planning.*March 1951: Herbert Morrison succeeds Ernest Bevin as Foreign Secretary. Lord Addison succeeds Morrison as President. Bevin succeeds Addison as Lord Privy Seal. James Chuter Ede succeeds Morrison as Leader of the House of Commons whilst remaining Home Secretary.*April 1951: Stokes succeeds Ernest Bevin as Lord Privy Seal. Robens succeeds Aneurin Bevan (resigned) as Minister of Labour and National Service. Sir Shawcross succeeds Harold Wilson (resigned) as President of the Board of Trade.Further readingClement Attlee published his memoirs, As it Happened, in 1954.Francis Williams A Prime Minister Remembers, based on interviews with Attlee, was published in 1961.Attlees other publications include:The Social Worker (1920);The Town Councillor (1925);The Will and the Way to Socialism (1935);The Labour Party in Perspective (1937);Collective Security Under the United Nations (1958);Empire into Commonwealth (1961).Biographies include:*Jenkins, Mr Attlee (1948)*Kenneth Harris, Attlee (1982)*Trevor Burridge, Clement Attlee: A Political Biography, (1985)*Francis Beckett, Clem Attlee (1997)*David Howell, Attlee (2006)*Nicklaus Thomas-Symonds, Attlee: A Life in Politics (2010)Biographies of Attlee and of his Cabinet can be found in:* Greg Rosen (ed) Dictionary of Labour Biography. Publishing. ISBN 1-902301-18-8The entry on Attlee in the of National Biography (DNB) was prepared by Shock, who as a Fellow of College, Oxford (Attlees alma mater), came to know Attlee personally in his later years.Accounts of the period include