__NOTOC__October 2003: January  February  March  April  May  June  July  August  September  October  November  DecemberEventsOctober 1, 2003* South Korean President Moo Hyun reiterates offer to the United States to consider a request for Korean participation in Force  Iraq in exchange for positive movement to resolve the standoff over North Koreas nuclear weapons program.* Anti-Americanism: A panel chosen by the administration of President George W. Bush concludes that the United States must drastically increase and overhaul its relations efforts to recast its image among Muslims and Arabs abroad. Hostility toward America has reached shocking levels ... What is required is not merely tactical adaptation but strategic, and radical, transformation. The panel adds that spin and manipulation are not the answer, nor is avoiding the debate.* of the European Commission Prodi unveils a proposal to boost flagging economic growth in Europe. The plan has two main parts: increasing spending on European transport networks and promoting research and development. * establishing a Constitution for Europe: Following talks with Prime Minister pidla on the draft Union constitution and the Republics position on the document, the Czech President Klaus decides not to travel to Rome and attend the forthcoming intergovernmental conference. * Canada: of the Northwest Territories Kakfwi announces he will not seek re-election in the November election.*The website 4chan.org is created.October 2, 2003* Korea claims to have already processed 8,000 rods from its nuclear reactor north of Pyongyang and is using the plutonium extracted during the process to make bombs to boost its nuclear capabilities for nuclear deterrent force. Citing a hostile policy by the United States, Vice Foreign Minister Su Hon states this is a means to safeguard the countrys territory. http://www.cnn.com/2003/WORLD/asiapcf/east/10/01/nkorea.nukes/index.html * of Iraq: The Nations Security Council discusses a new United States draft resolution on Iraq, which would enhance the Nations role in Iraq. Secretary General Annan states draft did not go in the direction he recommended.  A quicker transfer of sovereignty may change the dynamics on the ground, in terms of the security situation, and send a message. http://www.un.org/apps/news/story.asp?NewsID8436&Criraq&Cr1* Technology  Genome: The genome chip arrived with several companies rushing to sell the known human genes.  The products will allow scientists to scan all genes in a human tissue sample at once to determine which are active, with lower cost and increased speed. http://www.iht.com/articles/112288.html* relations: The States Navy blames the Peoples Republic of China for 2001 Island incident.  A report released to Defense Weekly under the Freedom of Information Act said that the pilot of the Chinese fighter made three passes at the U.S. propeller-driven plane over waters. On the third pass, the Chinese fighter hit a propeller on the American plane. http://www.washtimes.com/national//20030912-110434-9850r.htm* general election, 2003: McGuinty becomes the new premier of Ontario when his party defeats Evess incumbent Tories and Hamptons NDP.* M. Coetzee wins Prize for literature. http://www.nobel.se/literature/laureates/2003/press.html* Union: United States draft legislation which urges Pentagon to buy defence parts from American manufacturers has turned heads in Brussels, with some warning of yet another dispute at the WTO. http://www.euobserver.com/index.phtml?sid9&aid12889* Union: The first bilateral meeting between France and Austria since 1998 is marked by disagreements over the Constitution.  Austria heads the group of small countries seeking to make changes to the text, but France wants to leave the draft by Giscard dEstaing broadly untouched. http://www.euobserver.com/index.phtml?sid9&aid12888* Media: A on International Policy Attitudes (PIPA) study conducted with California-based Knowledge Networks, titled Misperceptions, 