List_of_computer_scientists
This is a list of well-known computer scientists, people who do work in science, in particular researchers and authors.Some persons notable as programmers are included here because they work in research as well as program. A few of these people pre-date the invention of the digital computer; they are now regarded as computer scientists because their work can be seen as leading to the invention of the computer. Others are mathematicians whose work falls within what would now be called theoretical computer science, such as complexity theory and information theory.A* van der Aalst  process management, mining, nets* Abelson  intersection of computing and teaching* Abiteboul  database theory* Abramsky  semantics* Adleman  RSA, computing* Agrawal  polynomial-time testing* von Ahn  computation* Aho  compilers book, the a in AWK* Nuwasiima  PHP Programming book* E. Allen  optimization* Scaranti  Image Processing, Image Retrieval* Amdahl  supercomputer developer, founder of Corporation* Annerl  multidimensional processing, computational complexity theory* Appel  compilers text books* Arora  theorem* E. Hugo - computing on heterogeneous multicore architectures * Vincent Atanasoff  computer pioneerB* Babbage  invented first mechanical computer* Bachman* Carl Backhouse  mathematics of program construction* Backus  FORTRAN, form* A. Bader* James Barr  System* Bayer  B-tree* C. Beatty, Jr.  compiler optimization,(http://www-03.ibm.com/press/us/en/pressrelease/22052.wss) super-computing(http://www.cs.clemson.edu/~mark/acs_people.html)* Bell  DEC VAX, Computer Structures* M. Bellovin  security* Berners-Lee  Wide Web* Bernus* Bjrner  Development Method (VDM), RAISE* Blaauw  one of the principal designers of the IBM 360 line of computers* Blum  cryptography* Boehm  software engineering economics, spiral development* Booch  Modeling Language, Management Group* Boole  logic* Bos  Style Sheets* Bowen  notation, methods* R. Bourne  shell, portable 68C compiler* S. Boyer  string searching, theorem prover* E. Bresenham  early computer graphics contributions including algorithm* J. Brown  Memory Architecture, Compatibility* Brinch Hansen (surname Brinch Hansen)  concurrency* Brinkkemper  methodology of product software development* Brooks  360, OS/360, Mythical Man-Month, Silver Bullet* Brooks* Burns  computing* Aaron Mwale  computer systemsC* Campbell-Kelly  of computing* Cardelli  objects* Cardie  language processing, summarization, learning* Catmull  graphics* Vinton Cerf  Internet, TCP/IP* Chaitin* Chaochen  calculus* (Susan) Cheng  networks* Church  mathematics of combinators, calculus* Ciobanu  process calculi, membrane computing* M. Clarke  checking* Cocke  RISC* F. Codd  formulated the database model* Colton  Computational Creativity* Justin Compton  Down Rules* Cormack  co-inventor of Markov compression* Cook  NP-completeness* Cooley  Fourier transform (FFT)* J. Corbat  Time-Sharing System (CTSS), Multics* Cousot  interpretation* Cray  Research, supercomputer* Cristianini  Machine learning, pattern analysis, intelligenceD* Dahl  Simula* van Dam  graphics, hypertext* J. Date  proponent of database model* Demaine  origami* DeMarco* E. Denning  security* J. Denning  identified the use of an systems set and balance set, President of ACM* Dertouzos  Director of Institute of Technology (MIT) Laboratory for Computer Science (LCS) from 1974 to 2001* Dewdney* Dham  P5 Pentium processor* Dietz* Diffie  cryptography* Dijkstra  algorithms, considered harmful, (programming)* Dongarra  algebra performance computing* Dorigo  colony optimization* Dourish  computer interaction* Stark Draper  Guidance Computer* Dumais  Retrieval* Dunkels  Protothreads* Dix  literally wrote the book on HCIE* Annie J. Easley* Ebbinkhuijsen  COBOL* Presper Eckert  ENIAC* Philip-Emeagwali  supercomputing* Allen Emerson  model checking* Engelbart  tiled windows, hypertext, mouse* Ershov* Riche Evans* C. Evans  graphics* EvenF* Fahlman* Fakhfakh* Feigenbaum  intelligence* Felten  security* Finin* Finkel* Firesmith* Flowers  computer* Floyd  NP-completeness* D. Foley* Forbus* W. Franke* P. FriedmanG* Gabriel* Galil* Galler  (programming language)* Garcia-Molina* Garey  NP-completeness* de Garis* Gelernter* Geschke* Ginsburg  languages, theory, AFL theory, theory* L. Glass* Gdel  computability  not a computer scientist per se, but his work was invaluable in the field* Goguen* Adele Goldberg  Smalltalk* Goldberg  cryptographer, messaging* Goldreich  cryptography, complexity theory* Goldwasser  cryptography, complexity theory* Golub  (math) computation* Charles Golumbic  graph theory* Gosling  NeWS, (programming language)* Paul Graham  Viaweb, Lisp, Arc* L. Graham  compilers, programming environments* Jim Gray  database* Greibach  normal form, AFL theory* Griswold  SNOBOL* Gropp  Passing Interface, PETSc* J. Grosz  Language Processing, Planning, Theory* Gruber* V. Guha  RDF, Netscape, (file format), Epinions* J. Gunther  performance analysis, planning* G. Gyarmati  adaptivity in operating systems and networkingH* Matthus Hahn  mechanical calculator* C. Hall  Guidance Computer* Halpern* Hamming  code, founder of the for Computing Machinery* Han  mining* Hartmanis  complexity theory* Hstad  complexity theory* Hatton  failure and vulnerabilities* Jifeng  provably correct systems* Hellman  encryption* Heiser  Development of L4 and founder of Labs* Hendler  Web* L. Hennessy  architecture* Herbert* Hillis  Machine* Hinton* B. Hirschberg  Linguistics* A. R. Hoare  Logic, rigor, sequential processes (CSP)* Henry Holland  algorithms* Hollerith  invented recording of data on a machine readable medium, using cards* Hopcroft  compilers* Admiral Hopper  compilers, COBOL* Horvitz - Intelligence* Householder* A. Huffman  codeI* Ichbiah  (programming language)* Ingalls - Bit_blit, Lively_Kernel* E. Iverson  (programming language), (programming language)J* Jacobson  Modeling Language, Management Group* Jain* James* S. Johnson* C. Johnson* Cliff Jones  Development 